# opsec-patterns.local — gitignored, machine-specific OPSEC patterns
#
# This is the CONTRACT file (tracked). Real values live in:
#   ~/.config/opsec-patterns.local          (machine-level, all repos)
#   ./.opsec-patterns.local                 (repo-level extras, optional)
#
# Both are gitignored by convention — the values themselves are OPSEC-sensitive
# (real hostnames, tailnet name, agent handles, codenames).
#
# Why machine-level: you commit to multiple repos from one machine. Defining
# the patterns once at $HOME/.config/ means every repo's hooks + lints read
# from the same source. No per-repo duplication, no drift.
#
# Format: one regex per line. Lines starting with `#` or blank lines are
# ignored. opsec-scan.sh joins them with `|` and wraps the group in \b(...)
# so agent handles like `ada` don't false-match inside `readable` or `metadata`.
#
# Setup (machine-level — applies to every repo you own):
#   mkdir -p ~/.config
#   cp hooks/opsec-patterns.local.example ~/.config/opsec-patterns.local
#   # edit ~/.config/opsec-patterns.local: replace examples below with your reals
#
# Setup (repo-level extras — only when a repo has project-specific patterns):
#   cp hooks/opsec-patterns.local.example ./.opsec-patterns.local
#   # edit ./.opsec-patterns.local
#   echo ".opsec-patterns.local" >> .gitignore
#
# Without either file present, opsec-scan.sh degrades gracefully: it runs only
# the hardcoded baseline (session IDs, Tailscale CGNAT IPs).

# === Hostnames (workstations, servers, exit nodes) ===
# One per line. Word boundaries are added automatically — `myhost` won't match
# inside `myhostname` but will match standalone `myhost`.
# Example placeholders (replace with your real hostnames):
my-workstation-name
homeserver-hostname
exit-node-region

# === Tailnet name ===
# The tailnet's DNS suffix (the part before .ts.net).
# Example placeholder:
my-tailnet-name

# === Codenames (internal-only projects, fleets, tools) ===
# Branded names for things that haven't shipped publicly. Functional
# descriptions in prose are always preferred over codenames.
# Example placeholders:
internal-codename-1
internal-codename-2

# === Agent handles (any identity that maps to a public chat/Matrix/etc handle) ===
# One per line. opsec-scan.sh wraps these in \b(...)\b automatically.
# Example placeholders:
agent-handle-1
agent-handle-2
agent-handle-3

# === Service names (internal-only daemons, bots, bridges) ===
# Example placeholders:
internal-service-1
internal-service-2
